Day 1 Day 2 Day 3 Day 4 Day 5 Day 6 Day 7 Day 8 Day 9 Day 10 Day 11 Day 12

A happy little grid puzzle :)
My initial approach was quite slow to run, so for part 2 I tried to cut down the search space by only checking rolls that had neighbours removed. After a bit of a convoluted refactor of my R part 2 solution I finally down to &lt;0.2s which is good enough for me.
One improvement was implementing a clunky queue in a matrix because I like seeing array indices, using start and end pointers. Another big improvement was going from searching in 8 directions from each position to find roll counts, to essentially shifting the whole grid 8 times and using vectorised addition.
I then slapped together a fully brute force Python solution and it runs in &lt;1s, sigh. Still, I was happy with my original time-to-solution.


